SIMPLE: appendage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Appendage
<hw>Ap*pend"age</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something appended
to, or accompanying, a principal or greater thing, though not necessary
to it, as a portico to a house.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Modesty is the <qex>appendage</qex> of sobriety.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A subordinate or subsidiary part
or organ; an external organ or limb, esp. of the articulates.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Antenn⟦ae⟧ and other <qex>appendages</qex> used for feeling.</q>
<rj><qau>Carpenter.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Addition; adjunct; concomitant.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Appendaged</ent>⟦br⟧
